Flight from Moscow
The collapse of communism gave the nations of the former Soviet bloc the chance to turn towards democracy, the market economy, and the rule of law.
Some of these countries decisively broke away from their communist past; others were less successful, and a few have catastrophically failed.
Moldova and Georgia belonged to the latter category until recently.
Their economic and political failure was largely due to – with active support from Russia – secessionist movements that sought to keep both countries within the "influence sphere" of the Kremlin.
As bloody conflicts erupted in Transnistria, Abkhazia, and South Ossetia, Russia transformed its military presence there into "peacekeeping forces" to maintain control.
For a long time, it was feared that these so-called "frozen conflicts" could suddenly turn hot.
This did not happen, and now we can speak of solutions – for both Georgia and Moldova have begun to achieve breakthroughs toward market economy and democracy.
The European Union's neighborhood policy has also contributed to this.
The starting point for these developments was the "Rose Revolution" in Georgia three years ago.
A state already dangerously close to failure, Georgia has now turned towards the West.
The success of various "color revolutions" in former Soviet states also sparked change in Moldova. Here, President Vladimir Voronin initiated reforms aimed at bringing the country closer to the EU.
These changes have spurred new initiatives in Georgia and Moldova to restore the territorial integrity of these countries through peaceful means.
Estonia's experience suggests how Georgia and Moldova should shape their policy towards Russia.
When Estonia became independent in 1991, Moscow sought to portray Estonia as a country with enormous economic problems unsuitable for investment.
Estonia was indeed poor, and its main export products were scrap metal and timber, but its economy was growing.
In Northeast Estonia, where the population was predominantly ethnically Russian and had settled there during the Soviet era, Russia supported what was called an "autonomy movement."
When Estonia resisted, Russia imposed sanctions and cut off gas supplies.
High taxes were levied on the few Estonian products that could be imported into Russia, and Russia even threatened with a military intervention.
But Estonia kept its cool.
The Russian sanctions even helped the country reorient its economy towards the West.
On the other hand, Western Europe did what it could to integrate the Baltic states – Lithuania, Latvia, and Estonia – and at the same time tried to avoid a conflict with Russia.
In 1994, a free trade agreement with the EU enabled Estonian products to find new markets, and ultimately made Estonia one of the most successful post-communist transition countries, joining the EU and NATO in 2004.
When Georgia became independent in 1991, it was not supported to the same extent by Western Europe.
Naturally, Georgia appeared less attractive as a partner than the Baltic states; the 1990s were characterized by coups, counter-coups, and civil wars, during which two regions – Abkhazia and South Ossetia – largely separated with Russian support.
The country has done its best to forget its bleak past.
Since the Rose Revolution, the economy has been reformed, the army strengthened, and the leadership of the country is young, dynamic, and eager to move the nation forward.
Thanks to Georgia's flat income tax of 12% – likely the lowest in the world – the national budget has increased.
The government has raised pensions and increased social benefits.
Corruption is decreasing, and a justice reform has been initiated.
The economy grew by 8% in 2005 and more than 10% in 2006.
Georgia is trying to ease tensions regarding Abkhazia and South Ossetia; however, Russia accuses the country of aggression and ethnic cleansing.
Its main goal is to prevent the West from supporting Georgia and hinder reconciliation with the breakaway regions.
The key powers involved are Russia and to some extent the United States.
Europe must show its relevance.
Estonia – at its independence and again during the recent crisis over the relocation of a Soviet-era monument – has shown that one can resist Russian pressure with determination and strong support.
Europe must understand that Georgia needs trade, not humanitarian aid.
Just as the free trade agreement with Europe enabled Estonia to find new markets, this could be the means by which the Georgians can help themselves.
Georgia has legitimate reason to hope that it will achieve genuine independence. But what about Moldova, the poorest country in Europe, which is more threatened by Russia than the Estonians or even the Georgians have ever been?
The lack of reform successes is partly the result of secessionist movements supported by Russia.
That the industrialized region of Transnistria – whose population speaks Russian and Ukrainian, mostly comprised of ethnic Moldovans of Romanian descent, planned closer ties with Romania – seceded from Moldova, dealt a severe blow to the country's independence right from the start.
A civil war followed, and in 1992, Russian troops entered Transnistria, where they remain today.
The independence of Transnistria was never recognized – neither by Moldova nor internationally.
It is said that there is lawlessness and corruption there.
Moldova is heavily indebted, unemployment is high, and its once-renowned wine industry is in decline.
Russia occasionally cuts off gas supplies, and many of the four million citizens have left the country.
Only Russia can solve the problem.
Government representatives from Moldova have made four unsuccessful trips to Moscow to persuade President Vladimir Putin to work on a solution and withdraw Russian troops.
Desperate Voronin asked for help from the EU observers Eubam, but an EU initiative requiring Russian cooperation was needed.
Unfortunately, it seems that the West lacks current insights into the situation in Moldova.
For example, in April, the EU and the USA only learned about a proposed peace agreement through a leak in Germany.
This agreement, it seems, would benefit Russia, as it intends to recognize Transnistria as a legitimate unit within Moldova.
If Russia has thus outmaneuvered the West, this would be a disastrous precedent for Georgia and other weak post-Soviet states.
